1
00:00:06,322 --> 00:00:08,279
Hey! Ow!

2
00:00:10,644 --> 00:00:12,833
Sorry. Didn't see you.

3
00:00:14,021 --> 00:00:16,161
Betty, is that-- is that you?

4
00:00:16,260 --> 00:00:18,668
I came back to pack
the rest of my things.

5
00:00:18,678 --> 00:00:20,430
Amanda left them on the floor.

6
00:00:20,440 --> 00:00:22,047
Oh, considerate of her.

7
00:00:22,057 --> 00:00:24,322
Thought it'd be better
if I came back at night,

8
00:00:24,766 --> 00:00:26,363
in case I cried,

9
00:00:26,373 --> 00:00:28,449
but so far, no tears.

10
00:00:28,458 --> 00:00:30,490
It's a new year, new job.

11
00:00:31,103 --> 00:00:33,727
It's just one floor down,
same building, same elevators.

12
00:00:33,736 --> 00:00:36,045
It's not like I'm never
gonna see any of you again.

13
00:00:36,054 --> 00:00:40,366
Still, I don't imagine
there's much swag at M.Y.W.

14
00:00:40,719 --> 00:00:41,862
No.

15
00:00:42,695 --> 00:00:45,051
I'll definitely miss the perks.

16
00:00:50,657 --> 00:00:53,783
Anyway, you know, I should probably get
going. I don't wanna miss the train.

17
00:00:53,798 --> 00:00:56,853
I think you'll find the trains run all night.
Can I just have a quick look at that bag?

18
00:00:56,888 --> 00:01:00,510
You know what? It's holding up
so beautifully, the quality...

19
00:01:00,527 --> 00:01:01,922
Give it here.

20
00:01:09,775 --> 00:01:11,353
This is a knockoff, isn't it?

21
00:01:11,368 --> 00:01:12,453
Christina...

22
00:01:12,468 --> 00:01:14,911
This looks like the bag that
the guy sells on the corner.

23
00:01:15,935 --> 00:01:19,223
Oh, this is the bag that
the guy sells on the corner.

24
00:01:19,237 --> 00:01:22,253
- I love it all the same.
- Betty, what happened to the Gucci?

25
00:01:22,266 --> 00:01:24,661
Nothing... bad.

26
00:01:24,675 --> 00:01:27,532
Nothing good,
if it's not hanging from your shoulder.

27
00:01:27,726 --> 00:01:29,090
Well, I can explain.

28
00:01:29,108 --> 00:01:30,493
Right. Start now.

29
00:01:30,508 --> 00:01:32,580
Okay... okay.

30
00:01:32,597 --> 00:01:37,730
So... well, it all started with
the stampede. Four months ago...

31
00:01:49,427 --> 00:01:50,851
No, I gotta go.

32
00:01:52,316 --> 00:01:53,681
Did I miss it?

33
00:01:54,125 --> 00:01:57,743
Crap! Crap, crap! Crap!

34
00:01:57,995 --> 00:01:59,873
Dignity, Amanda.

35
00:02:01,695 --> 00:02:03,812
I guess it's too
late for that now.

36
00:02:04,575 --> 00:02:06,872
Prada trumps passion, Daniel.

37
00:02:07,137 --> 00:02:09,202
Christina just posted
the sign-up sheet.

38
00:02:09,217 --> 00:02:10,482
Sign-up sheet?

39
00:02:10,498 --> 00:02:12,671
She's cleaning the
closet tomorrow--

40
00:02:12,685 --> 00:02:16,302
the winter fashions from the last three
issues. Christina needs to get rid of them

41
00:02:16,315 --> 00:02:18,722
to make room for the spring
collections coming in.

42
00:02:18,736 --> 00:02:21,523
Freebie couture is
the staff perk.

43
00:02:21,535 --> 00:02:23,883
You know, you really should
take a trip down there, Betty.

44
00:02:23,897 --> 00:02:27,180
They might have some...
socks in your size.

45
00:02:28,958 --> 00:02:29,990
Okay.

46
00:02:30,008 --> 00:02:31,653
That the stuff on Oshi?

47
00:02:31,807 --> 00:02:32,901
Yes.

48
00:02:33,235 --> 00:02:35,733
Back issues with his fall
and winter collections,

49
00:02:35,747 --> 00:02:39,633
a profile from last february's
interview and his autobiography.

50
00:02:39,647 --> 00:02:40,783
He has an autobiography?

51
00:02:40,795 --> 00:02:43,353
"Oshi on Oshi," by Oshi.

52
00:02:45,345 --> 00:02:47,871
I think those are supposed
to be his glasses.

53
00:02:48,056 --> 00:02:51,072
Super-sized icon of
minimal fashion, Oshi,

54
00:02:51,085 --> 00:02:53,841
will be steamrolling
into Gotham tomorrow

55
00:02:53,858 --> 00:02:57,010
to unveil his spring collection
to the editors of "Mode,"

56
00:02:57,026 --> 00:03:00,502
where he debuted his
collections for years,

57
00:03:00,517 --> 00:03:03,550
due to his extremely
close friendship

58
00:03:03,565 --> 00:03:06,280
with former editor-in-chief,
Fey Sommers.

59
00:03:06,298 --> 00:03:10,852
Fey's tragic death in a
fiery car crash last month

60
00:03:10,867 --> 00:03:12,953
left him devastated.

61
00:03:12,966 --> 00:03:17,270
Fey was so... minimal.

62
00:03:19,296 --> 00:03:21,830
And now the question
on everybody's mind--

63
00:03:21,846 --> 00:03:25,441
will the fashion heavyweight hit
it off with Fey's replacement,

64
00:03:25,455 --> 00:03:28,400
himbo playboy Daniel Meade?

65
00:03:28,415 --> 00:03:30,800
I'm thinking no-shi.

66
00:03:30,816 --> 00:03:33,210
Well, I'm thinking yes-shi.

67
00:03:33,498 --> 00:03:35,152
Thanks, I appreciate
that, Betty,

68
00:03:35,167 --> 00:03:37,033
but we need Oshi business,

69
00:03:37,046 --> 00:03:40,110
and I have nothing in common with
the man, I don't speak japanese,

70
00:03:40,126 --> 00:03:43,351
I don't wear white, I have never
eaten an entire shark at one meal.

71
00:03:43,367 --> 00:03:44,800
He'll love you, Daniel.

72
00:03:44,815 --> 00:03:46,771
It's all about relationships
with the japanese.

73
00:03:46,785 --> 00:03:48,730
My  first meal with
him has to be perfect.

74
00:03:48,746 --> 00:03:51,140
Well, you have the chef's table
at Masa on wednesday night

75
00:03:51,156 --> 00:03:53,053
- at 8:00 p.m...
- Oh, I love their uni.

76
00:03:53,067 --> 00:03:55,982
And I got you this japanese
customs and phrase book.

77
00:03:55,995 --> 00:03:59,183
You should also know that your
credit card was rejected.

78
00:03:59,198 --> 00:04:02,023
- That's my personal card.
- That's the one you gave me.

79
00:04:02,036 --> 00:04:04,580
Betty, you always use the
company card for business.

80
00:04:04,595 --> 00:04:07,203
That reminds me-- you're gonna take
care of my expense report, right?

81
00:04:07,237 --> 00:04:09,041
- Expense report?
- Yeah, Henry something-or-other

82
00:04:09,075 --> 00:04:11,550
from accounting sent us a memo,
says it was due today.

83
00:04:11,567 --> 00:04:13,492
Today? No, I didn't get this.

84
00:04:13,507 --> 00:04:15,333
Well, it says you were copied.

85
00:04:15,686 --> 00:04:17,692
No. No, I didn't get this.

86
00:04:17,706 --> 00:04:20,013
Well, get on it.
My father's a hard-ass on expenses,

87
00:04:20,027 --> 00:04:22,713
and the company's not gonna
reimburse me if we turn that in late.

88
00:04:22,728 --> 00:04:26,153
Accounting is giving us till 10:30
tomorrow morning to get it in--period.

89
00:04:26,168 --> 00:04:28,822
- No exceptions.
- But do you have any receipts?

90
00:04:31,586 --> 00:04:33,832
You know what to do
with them, right?

91
00:04:33,895 --> 00:04:35,140
Payroll.

92
00:04:38,218 --> 00:04:39,892
- Mr. Meade...
- Thank you.

93
00:04:39,905 --> 00:04:42,562
- And you are?
- Betty Suarez.

94
00:04:44,155 --> 00:04:46,682
- This is my first paycheck.
- Mine, too.

95
00:04:47,168 --> 00:04:49,171
- What the...
- F.I.C.A.?

96
00:04:49,187 --> 00:04:52,563
Now Manny Epstein was a good publisher
when Fey was running the show.

97
00:04:52,575 --> 00:04:55,820
She was, however,
fiscally responsible.

98
00:04:55,835 --> 00:05:00,293
Daniel... well,
Daniel needs stronger supervision.

99
00:05:00,515 --> 00:05:02,951
He's a little indulged,
but he's growing up.

100
00:05:02,965 --> 00:05:05,391
He ran through his trust
fund in three years.

101
00:05:05,405 --> 00:05:09,631
For his 28th birthday,
he tried to buy an island... and J-Lo.

102
00:05:09,645 --> 00:05:11,130
Shakira.

103
00:05:11,198 --> 00:05:13,560
They were wild oats.
He's turned the corner.

104
00:05:13,578 --> 00:05:15,500
We're talking about
a magazine, Bradford.

105
00:05:15,517 --> 00:05:17,313
Why would you want
the publisher's job?

106
00:05:17,325 --> 00:05:20,450
It's financial--budgets,
ad sales.

107
00:05:20,468 --> 00:05:21,451
You're creative.

108
00:05:21,468 --> 00:05:25,591
I never said I'd give up my creative
title, just add "publisher" to it.

109
00:05:25,608 --> 00:05:28,073
Better to keep
Daniel reined in.

110
00:05:28,088 --> 00:05:30,893
I'd rather you concentrated
on the job at hand--

111
00:05:30,907 --> 00:05:33,943
helping Daniel establish
a relationship with Oshi.

112
00:05:33,957 --> 00:05:36,403
His exclusives are
worth millions to us.

113
00:05:36,415 --> 00:05:38,200
Oh, he'll make an impression.

114
00:05:39,016 --> 00:05:40,592
I guarantee it.

115
00:05:41,848 --> 00:05:44,080
The Gucci shoulder bag is mine!

116
00:05:44,097 --> 00:05:47,122
Nice, but over it. Those Louboutin
boots, on the other hand...

117
00:05:47,137 --> 00:05:49,521
As if you stand a
chance of getting them.

118
00:05:49,536 --> 00:05:51,430
- I can trade.
- With what?

119
00:05:51,445 --> 00:05:53,281
You're last on the list.

120
00:05:53,298 --> 00:05:55,733
All that'll be left are those
gag-awful Pucci scarves.

121
00:05:55,746 --> 00:05:59,233
I, on the other hand,
have the pick of the closet,

122
00:05:59,245 --> 00:06:02,250
and numero uno picks
the glorious "it" bag

123
00:06:02,267 --> 00:06:04,062
from the house of Gucci.

124
00:06:04,077 --> 00:06:05,930
Why would you need
a pocketbook?

125
00:06:05,948 --> 00:06:10,121
I need it to trade.
At "Mode," fashion is currency.

126
00:06:10,135 --> 00:06:13,040
I know that's hard for you to understand,
because you're so very much in debt,

127
00:06:13,077 --> 00:06:16,530
but, for instance, 
if I needed a favor from you,

128
00:06:16,546 --> 00:06:18,851
like an invitation to a
Marc Jacobs dinner party,

129
00:06:18,868 --> 00:06:22,661
then I might be persuaded to trade
that favor for my fabulous Gucci bag,

130
00:06:22,678 --> 00:06:24,943
which you so desperately need.

131
00:06:31,335 --> 00:06:32,833
Loiter much?

132
00:06:32,847 --> 00:06:37,093
Oh, um, I need some help,
if you wouldn't mind.

133
00:06:37,105 --> 00:06:40,561
Ah! You need a favor.

134
00:06:40,575 --> 00:06:42,623
Yes, I guess a favor.

135
00:06:42,685 --> 00:06:46,311
Um,  I seem to be late in getting
in Daniel's expense report,

136
00:06:46,325 --> 00:06:49,182
and I don't know why I didn't
get the memo from accounting.

137
00:06:49,195 --> 00:06:51,860
Hmm,  must have been
lost in the mailroom.

138
00:06:51,878 --> 00:06:52,882
Oops.

139
00:06:52,897 --> 00:06:55,271
And I'm kind of lost
on how to do it.

140
00:06:55,305 --> 00:06:57,601
Marc'll be happy to help you.
Won't you, Marc?

141
00:06:57,616 --> 00:07:01,643
Please give Betty the correct form,
and then give her a copy of our repo.

142
00:07:01,657 --> 00:07:04,741
If she does what we did,
she'll be fine.

143
00:07:08,906 --> 00:07:13,420
You realize this means an
unnamed favor at a later date.

144
00:07:14,133 --> 00:07:15,677
I understand.

145
00:07:16,086 --> 00:07:17,635
Thank you.

146
00:07:17,884 --> 00:07:19,596
- Ta.
- Ta.

147
00:07:19,959 --> 00:07:23,430
Oh, oh, oh, oh, oh,
oh, oh, oh, oh, oh.

148
00:07:23,447 --> 00:07:25,133
It's Betty's memo.

149
00:07:25,145 --> 00:07:29,652
Those boys in the mailroom--
cute, but so careless.

150
00:07:32,158 --> 00:07:33,483
Nice bag.

151
00:07:33,495 --> 00:07:34,851
Oh, thank you.

152
00:07:34,868 --> 00:07:37,652
So... Juan Valdez.

153
00:07:38,178 --> 00:07:40,173
Did it come with a mule?

154
00:07:41,255 --> 00:07:44,321
- Christina!
- You look fabulous...

155
00:07:45,386 --> 00:07:46,943
Sod off!

156
00:07:46,958 --> 00:07:49,772
Four times a year,
I'm everybody's best friend.

157
00:07:49,785 --> 00:07:52,271
Well, nobody is moving
up the list, okay?

158
00:07:52,286 --> 00:07:55,053
Nobody, and that
includes you, Amanda.

159
00:07:55,876 --> 00:07:58,891
I was late signing up
because of my job.

160
00:07:58,905 --> 00:08:02,162
Oh, and we all know what kind
of job you were giving-- doing.

161
00:08:02,257 --> 00:08:05,241
Well, where were you?
I'd have let you cut the queue.

162
00:08:05,258 --> 00:08:08,263
Christina, you don't have
anything larger than a size 6.

163
00:08:08,275 --> 00:08:10,012
I have accessories.

164
00:08:10,168 --> 00:08:12,982
I know it sounds stupid,
but I'm just not that into fashion.

165
00:08:12,997 --> 00:08:14,710
Forget the fashion.
Did you get your paycheck?

166
00:08:14,745 --> 00:08:18,032
Yes, and I spent, like,
half of it on a slice of pizza.

167
00:08:18,047 --> 00:08:19,703
They take so much out.

168
00:08:19,718 --> 00:08:21,952
That's why you need the
swag from the closet.

169
00:08:21,965 --> 00:08:23,600
- Swag?
- The goodies.

170
00:08:23,615 --> 00:08:25,380
Gotta start thinking of
it as part of your wages.

171
00:08:25,416 --> 00:08:26,561
Look.

172
00:08:26,576 --> 00:08:30,532
Don't you just love it?
Now that is the "it" bag of the season.

173
00:08:30,545 --> 00:08:31,680
It's true art.

174
00:08:31,698 --> 00:08:35,462
Look at the way the buckles offset
the pattern. It just slays me.

175
00:08:35,477 --> 00:08:38,381
You know, my mom used to
have a bag just like this.

176
00:08:38,395 --> 00:08:40,711
She gave it to me when I was,
like, 3.

177
00:08:40,726 --> 00:08:43,121
I used to carry
my crayons in it.

178
00:08:43,808 --> 00:08:46,140
Made my sister furious.

179
00:08:46,297 --> 00:08:48,070
Hey, lovely ladies.

180
00:08:48,085 --> 00:08:50,511
200 bucks, and you can't
tell it from the real thing.

181
00:08:50,526 --> 00:08:52,111
Yeah, he can't tell
it from a Gucci.

182
00:08:52,126 --> 00:08:54,970
Believe me, you walkin to "Mode" with
a knockoff, you might as well walk in

183
00:08:55,008 --> 00:08:57,541
with a cow bladder.
Everybody knows.

184
00:08:58,165 --> 00:09:00,633
He did all this
damage in a month?

185
00:09:00,645 --> 00:09:04,041
Well, dad, he's an editor-in-chief.
He's gotta entertain people.

186
00:09:04,065 --> 00:09:05,980
- What's Bow-oo-lay?
- Bouley--

187
00:09:05,996 --> 00:09:07,993
only the hottest
restaurant in Tribeca.

188
00:09:08,008 --> 00:09:10,182
He spent $821 on dinner.

189
00:09:10,195 --> 00:09:13,211
Ooh! Next time we go to the chicken
place, I'm ordering all white meat,

190
00:09:13,225 --> 00:09:14,932
- and I don't wanna hear about it.
- You guys don't understand.

191
00:09:14,966 --> 00:09:18,552
This is business. He's entertaining
models and advertisers and designers,

192
00:09:18,565 --> 00:09:20,980
- and what's that say on the back?
- It's a blank.

193
00:09:21,256 --> 00:09:23,500
Another miscellaneous expense.

194
00:09:23,517 --> 00:09:25,742
There's a lot of
miscellaneous expenses.

195
00:09:25,758 --> 00:09:28,953
I guess that's fine. Most of Wilhelmina's
expenses are miscellaneous, too.

196
00:09:28,967 --> 00:09:30,413
Says she went to Rio.

197
00:09:30,426 --> 00:09:32,603
Yeah, she's the creative director.
It was a fashion shoot.

198
00:09:32,637 --> 00:09:33,873
It was in the last issue.

199
00:09:33,887 --> 00:09:38,702
Oh, $25,000 to Casa Brazil
for props and extras?

200
00:09:38,716 --> 00:09:41,071
Ay, dios, and they haven't
given you a paycheck yet?

201
00:09:41,087 --> 00:09:42,953
Well, actually,
they gave it to me today.

202
00:09:42,967 --> 00:09:44,381
And?

203
00:09:49,438 --> 00:09:52,601
Someone is blowing
25 grand in Rio,

204
00:09:52,617 --> 00:09:54,302
and this is what
they're paying you?

205
00:09:54,316 --> 00:09:56,671
She's not doing it for the money, Hilda.
It's an opportunity.

206
00:09:56,706 --> 00:10:01,403
Well, maybe you should get another
job to support your opportunity.

207
00:10:01,627 --> 00:10:03,092
Ay, dios mío.

208
00:10:03,107 --> 00:10:04,892
They take so much out.

209
00:10:05,438 --> 00:10:08,181
Well, it's still
a paycheck, Betty.

210
00:10:08,196 --> 00:10:10,130
It's more than I made
on my first job.

211
00:10:10,406 --> 00:10:12,321
Vamos. Come on.

212
00:10:12,335 --> 00:10:13,690
Novela's waiting.

213
00:10:15,845 --> 00:10:16,823
Betty...

214
00:10:19,797 --> 00:10:22,423
we have to make some
serious cutbacks.

215
00:10:23,118 --> 00:10:25,462
The pharma wouldn't fill
his prescription today.

216
00:10:25,476 --> 00:10:26,653
What?

217
00:10:27,045 --> 00:10:30,850
Maria Ortiz--she can't do that.
She knows he needs his pills to work.

218
00:10:30,867 --> 00:10:32,760
He has arrhythmia.
He could die.

219
00:10:32,776 --> 00:10:34,141
It wasn't Maria.

220
00:10:34,157 --> 00:10:37,430
It's his H.M.O.
They're not gonna cover him anymore.

221
00:10:40,295 --> 00:10:43,393
Transcript : Raceman
Subtitles : Willow's Team

222
00:10:43,405 --> 00:10:46,502
www.forom.com

223
00:10:51,348 --> 00:10:54,253
So this was around the time
Walter and I were broken up.

224
00:10:54,265 --> 00:10:56,240
You remember how he
was stalking me?

225
00:11:07,095 --> 00:11:08,973
Stop following me, Walter!

226
00:11:08,985 --> 00:11:10,790
I have something for you.

227
00:11:10,806 --> 00:11:13,410
I don't need any more batteries,
thank you.

228
00:11:13,425 --> 00:11:15,152
It's a universal remote.

229
00:11:15,166 --> 00:11:17,221
We only have one TV.

230
00:11:17,238 --> 00:11:18,812
Now leave me alone.

231
00:11:24,786 --> 00:11:27,853
- Walter...
- I'm going to get you back, Betty.

232
00:11:27,865 --> 00:11:29,571
Not by stalking me.

233
00:11:29,696 --> 00:11:32,421
You cheated on me, Walter.
You cheated on me

234
00:11:32,438 --> 00:11:35,090
with Gina Gambarro.
Do you even understand what that means?

235
00:11:35,105 --> 00:11:38,390
I don't care how many
universal remotes you give me.

236
00:11:38,886 --> 00:11:41,043
There's no winning me back.

237
00:11:45,815 --> 00:11:48,531
Your father's H.M.O.
file is under investigation.

238
00:11:48,547 --> 00:11:49,942
What kind of investigation?

239
00:11:49,958 --> 00:11:51,673
I don't know.
They don't tell me those things.

240
00:11:51,707 --> 00:11:53,693
All I know is that they refuse
to cover his prescription

241
00:11:53,726 --> 00:11:55,521
until the matter's resolved.

